    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thx. i saw something about how dirt or even bugs can get in there and mess things up. what kind of stuff usually causes those blockages? like is it just random debris or is there anything specific that pilots have to watch out for?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, the most common culprits are often small insects, dust, or ice that gets trapped in the tiny opening of the tube. Pilots specifically have to watch out for bugs during takeoff and landing when the plane is moving slowly, as well as ice accumulation in cold, wet conditions. While random debris like sand is possible, it is usually the combination of low speed and moisture that creates the perfect environment for these blockages to occur.\n\nTo prevent this, many aircraft have pitot heat systems that blow warm air through the tube to melt ice or dislodge debris. If your manual mentions a specific \"pitot tube\" issue, it might be referring to a more complex blockage caused by a combination of factors, but generally, it is just the air rushing in that gets stopped up. This is why pilots are trained to recognize when their airspeed indicator behaves strangely, as it is a classic sign of a blocked pitot tube.\n\nIf you are reading about a specific incident where a bug or dirt caused a problem, it is likely because the tube was sitting idle or moving too slowly for that debris to be blown away. The good news is that modern aircraft often have backup systems or visual checks to help pilots spot these",
      "source": "target",
